---
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";

const phases = [
  [
    "Phase 1 — Surveys.",
    "We designed and distributed a 12-question survey to 30 students across three grade levels. Questions covered self-reported focus duration, phone usage patterns during study, anxiety levels, and study environment. Data collection is complete; analysis is ongoing.",
  ],
  [
    "Phase 2 — Interviews.",
    "We are conducting semi-structured interviews with 6–8 survey respondents selected for range of response patterns. The goal is to understand the qualitative experience of distraction in ways the survey instrument could not capture.",
  ],
  [
    "Phase 3 — Literature review.",
    "We are reading primary sources on social facilitation (Zajonc, 1965), co-regulation of learning, smartphone-mediated distraction, and gamification. A working annotated bibliography is on the Research page.",
  ],
  [
    "Phase 4 — Prototype testing.",
    "We are building Cohort, a lightweight web app that lets 3–6 students join a shared study session and see each other's focus status in real time, without any competitive or scoring mechanisms. We will run structured testing sessions with volunteer students during the exam period in fall 2026.",
  ],
  [
    "Phase 5 — Paper.",
    "The project concludes with a written research paper synthesizing all phases. Target completion: January 2027.",
  ],
];
---

<Base title="About">
  <h1>About the research</h1>
  <p class="label">Research question, hypothesis, and methodology</p>

  <div class="prose">
    <div class="block">
      <p class="block-label">Research question</p>
      <p>
        To what extent does social presence — defined as the awareness of others
        engaging in the same task simultaneously — improve sustained focus among
        high school students during high-stakes study conditions? And how does
        this effect, if it exists, compare to gamification-based study
        interventions?
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="block">
      <p class="block-label">Current hypothesis</p>
      <p>
        We hypothesize that social presence, independent of competition or
        reward mechanisms, produces a meaningful improvement in self-reported
        focus duration among high school students during finals-season study
        sessions. We further hypothesize that this effect is most pronounced
        among students who report moderate-to-high baseline anxiety, and that it
        does not require synchronous communication — shared presence alone may be
        sufficient.
      </p>
      <p class="muted">
        We do not yet have data to support this. The hypothesis is based on
        preliminary survey results, informal interviews, and our reading of
        literature on social facilitation and co-regulation of learning. We
        expect it to change as testing proceeds.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="block">
      <p class="block-label">Methodology</p>
      {
        phases.map(([label, text]) => (
          <p>
            <strong>{label}</strong> {text}
          </p>
        ))
      }
    </div>

    <div class="block">
      <p class="block-label">Limitations we already know about</p>
      <p class="muted">
        Our sample is small and geographically constrained to one school.
        Respondents were recruited through personal networks, introducing
        selection bias toward students who are already reflective about their
        study habits. Cohort testing will be unblinded and self-selected. We are
        not trained researchers and may be making methodological errors we
        haven't identified yet. We will acknowledge these limitations in the
        paper.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</Base>

<style>
  .block {
    margin-bottom: 2.75rem;
  }

  .block:last-child {
    margin-bottom: 0;
  }

  .block-label {
    font-family: var(--font-sans);
    font-size: 0.75rem;
    letter-spacing: 0.16em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--muted-foreground);
    margin: 0 0 0.85rem;
  }
</style>
